subsection.p:
Standard Symbols. Frequently used sets are usually given symbols that are reserved for them alone. For example, since we will be referring to the positive integers throughout this book, we will use the symbol \mathbb{P} instead of writing \{1, 2, 3, \ldots \}. A few of the other sets of numbers that we will use frequently are:
\mathbb{N} for the natural numbers, \{0, 1, 2, 3, \ldots \}
mathbb{Z} for the integers, \{\ldots $, -3,-2,-1,0,1,2,3,$\ldots \}
\mathbb{Q} for the rational numbers
\mathbb{R} for the real numbers
\mathbb{C} for the complex numbers}.

exercise.statement:
 List four elements of each of the following sets:


 \{k \in  \mathbb{P} \mid {k - 1} \textrm{ is a multiple of 7}\} 

 \{x \mid x \textrm{ is a fruit and its skin is normally eaten }\}

\{x \in \mathbb{Q}\mid x\in \mathbb{Z}\}

 \{2n \mid n \in \mathbb{Z}, n < 0 \}

 \{s \mid s = 1 + 2 + \cdots  + n, n \in \mathbb{P}\}

 List all elements of the following sets:


\{\frac{1}{n} \mid n \in \{3,4,5,6\}\} 


 \{\alpha \in  \textrm{the alphabet} \mid  \textrm{\alpha precedes F\ } 


\{-k \mid k \in \mathbb{P}\} 


\{n^2 \mid  n = -2, -1, 0, 1, 2\} 


\{n \in  \mathbb{P} \mid n \textrm{is a  factor of  24 }\}

  Describe the following sets using set-builder notation. 


 \{ 5, 7, 9, \text{...} , 77, 79\} 


the rational numbers that are strictly between -1 and 1 


 the even integers


 \{-18, -9,0,9, 18,27, . . .\}

